WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.460
&gt;&gt; Again, welcome. We're very honored to have
with us today a noted sociologist, philosopher,

00:00:05.460 --> 00:00:10.080
cultural critic, Slavoj Zizek. Slavoj is a
senior research, right, in the Institute of

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:15.840
Sociology at the University of Lubljana in
Slovenia, a professor in the European Graduate

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:19.231
School. He has been a visiting professor at
several universities including the University

00:00:19.231 --> 00:00:23.980
of Chicago, Columbia, Princeton, and many
others. And he's currently the international

00:00:23.980 --> 00:00:30.050
director of Birkbeck Institute for the Humanities
at Birkbeck College in the University of London.

00:00:30.050 --> 00:00:34.320
The Wikipedian horde has deemed him an intellectual
outsider and a confrontational maverick. And

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:38.590
he comes to us today to discuss his recent
book "Violence" a book which challenges us

00:00:38.590 --> 00:00:42.330
to look deeper in to the topic of violence.
To see beyond the ephemeral manifestations

00:00:42.330 --> 00:00:47.790
of violence, gunshot and explosion, the clash
of metal on metal, blood stains, and to discuss

00:00:47.790 --> 00:00:51.840
systemic violence, the violence inherent in
our systems of living our way of life. And

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:56.190
in a sense our age is an age--of the age of
technological and biological exploration is

00:00:56.190 --> 00:01:00.330
an age of philosophical exploration as well.
I know that many of us at Google are familiar

00:01:00.330 --> 00:01:05.840
with this. And to quote Slavoj himself which
I found on the Internet, of course, "The age

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:12.740
of philosophy is in a sense, again, that we
are confronted more and more often with philosophical

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:16.530
problems in everyday level. It is not just
that you withdraw from daily life into a world

00:01:16.530 --> 00:01:20.539
of philosophical contemplation; on the contrary,
you cannot find your way around daily life

00:01:20.539 --> 00:01:24.689
itself without answering certain philosophical
questions is unique time when everyone is

00:01:24.689 --> 00:01:28.649
in a way are forced to be some kind of philosopher."
So, let's take this opportunity, please, for

00:01:28.649 --> 00:01:35.679
everyday philosophy and welcomes Slavoj Zizek
to Google

00:01:35.679 --> 00:01:40.990
&gt;&gt; ZIZEK: I hope this works, yeah. Thanks
very much, I'm really glad of being here,

00:01:40.990 --> 00:01:45.520
you know why, because let me begin with a
funny association which came on my mind now.

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:54.240
You know of what from my communist youth,
this scene here now reminds me. And the communism

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:59.759
when I was young, you'd not only have to work
in factories in Slovenia but you get so called

00:01:59.759 --> 00:02:05.469
hours of ideological education, you know like,
exactly like now, like, during lunch time,

00:02:05.469 --> 00:02:11.220
workers has to sit through some boring short
talk which ruin your lunch about, I don’t

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:15.980
know, great result of our construction of
socialism and so on, and so on. I feel right

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:22.630
back in those times, well, sorry for ruining
your lunch. So, in contrast to the kindness

00:02:22.630 --> 00:02:28.460
of the good guy who introduced me, I would
say, please, don’t let me terrorize you

00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:35.730
if your mind is with your computer, go on,
go on. I would feel better about it. What--I

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:41.730
was thinking about what to do here, of course,
I don’t want to give the resume of a book.

00:02:41.730 --> 00:02:48.350
I never was able to be so arrogant, like,
I know some guys. Poet and so on who treat

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:54.130
themselves as classics, you know, like, they
open their own book, read a paragraph and

00:02:54.130 --> 00:03:00.620
say, "Let's now look at what the thinker wanted
to say," now, I will--the proper dialectical

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:07.480
way to approach this book is, I think, to
do the opposite of the book. To focus not

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:17.180
on violence but on what violence reacts to,
usually on the everyday texture of our lives,

00:03:17.180 --> 00:03:24.280
everyday ideology. Now, your first reaction
probably would [INDISTINCT] here but aren’t

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:31.520
we beyond ideology? I mean, am I an old Marxist
from, you know, like, the species which basically

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:37.950
died around 1990 who still believe in big
causes and so on. No, I will try to convince

00:03:37.950 --> 00:03:46.290
you that ideology is, of course, not in the
sense of big world view vision to impose on

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:52.930
society, but ideology in the sense of complicated
network of ethical, political, social, whatever

00:03:52.930 --> 00:03:59.900
prejudices, which, even if we are unaware
of them, still determines the way we function.

00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:05.220
It's still something which structures our
lives. What is ideology? Maybe some of you

00:04:05.220 --> 00:04:14.100
know this but I cannot resist repeating this
story because it works perfectly, namely,

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:20.730
do you remember? You must, my God; it was
endlessly reproduced on Google. That unfortunate

00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:30.200
interview of Donald Rumsfeld some five years
ago just before the Gulf War when he wanted

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:38.360
to explain why, where is the danger of Saddam
and he used his famous parallel--he basically,

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:46.040
they have a whole theory of knowledge claiming
that there are--you remember, known knowns,

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:52.650
things we know that we know. Then, like, we
know that Saddam is the boss of Iraq. Then

00:04:52.650 --> 00:05:01.650
he went on--there are, there are known unknowns.
There are things we know that we don’t know.

00:05:01.650 --> 00:05:07.389
Like, for example, I don’t know--I know
there are some cars in front of this building

00:05:07.389 --> 00:05:13.070
but I don’t know how many they are. But
I know that I don’t know this, you know.

00:05:13.070 --> 00:05:19.460
Then he went on, there are unknown unknowns.
In the sense of things that we even don’t

00:05:19.460 --> 00:05:27.310
know that we don’t know then. Like, his
ideas was--the known unknown was how many

00:05:27.310 --> 00:05:33.660
and where Saddam has his weapons of mass destruction,
like, we don’t know but we know that we

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:38.460
don’t know. But then his paranoia was what
if there are unknown unknowns, some secret

00:05:38.460 --> 00:05:45.389
weapons that we don’t even know what they
are, yet, they're more radically unknown.

00:05:45.389 --> 00:05:51.520
Now, my claim is that--okay, there goes this
idea, my claim, my joke here is that if you

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:56.910
have a little bit of a sense for structural
analysis thinking, you’ll see immediately

00:05:56.910 --> 00:06:02.600
that something is missing here, a fourth term,
known knowns, we know what we know. Known

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:09.220
unknowns, we know what we don’t know, or
then, unknown unknowns, the totally other,

00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:14.430
like, we don’t even know what we don’t
know. Something is missing the most interesting

00:06:14.430 --> 00:06:22.330
category, not the unknown, not the known unknowns,
but the un-unknown knowns, not think we know

00:06:22.330 --> 00:06:28.300
that we don’t know, but think we don’t
know that we know, that’s the unconscious

00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:32.691
[INDISTINCT] ideologically. Although silent
prejudices, which determine how we act, how

00:06:32.691 --> 00:06:42.830
we react, and we, in a way, there are so much
the texture in to which we are embedded, that

00:06:42.830 --> 00:06:50.640
we literally don’t even know that we know
them. And I think this was why you were in

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:57.860
such trouble in Iraq. Not so much that you,
there was some mystery that you didn’t know.

00:06:57.860 --> 00:07:02.940
The U.S. Army and administration basically
didn’t know what they already know. All

00:07:02.940 --> 00:07:05.440
the unconscious political military prejudices
as it where which determined their activity,

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:12.979
which is why I don’t know if some of you
know it or not. To give you another example,

00:07:12.979 --> 00:07:18.250
I'm sorry of repeating myself; I hope you
are a new public here. The analysis--because

00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:22.550
of which and again it was mocked endlessly
in Google. It brought me some negative thing

00:07:22.550 --> 00:07:30.669
but I still think it works perfectly. Or these
unknown knowns are the structure of toilets

00:07:30.669 --> 00:07:36.490
in our Western civilization. It's ideology
at its purest. Now, will you say, am I crazy?

00:07:36.490 --> 00:07:42.449
Where is ideology? Did you notice something,
I simplified the analysis but I know I simplified

00:07:42.449 --> 00:07:51.830
but basically it's called cycling [ph]. What
do we get? We get three basic types of toilets.

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:58.830
The French one, where, sorry for relative
vulgarity, where the hole is in the back of

00:07:58.830 --> 00:08:04.949
the toilet so that shit falls directly into
the hole and disappears--I mean, not the hole,

00:08:04.949 --> 00:08:11.490
I mean, not just the bowl but the hole where
it then, you know, get in. Then we have the

00:08:11.490 --> 00:08:18.229
German type where the hole, where the shit
disappears is in front so that the shit is

00:08:18.229 --> 00:08:24.120
somehow displayed there. You know Germans
have all this ritual of, I'm not kidding,

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:29.370
around 50 percent of toilets, check it up,
if you go to Germany are still structured

00:08:29.370 --> 00:08:33.820
like this that the shit is displayed there
and they have this old ritual, every morning

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:40.680
you should smell your shit, check it for traces
of, I mean, Erica Yong, in her Fear of Flying

00:08:40.680 --> 00:08:46.700
makes wonderful a comment, she said, she writes,
“A nation which get such toilets, they--no

00:08:46.700 --> 00:08:53.350
wonder, they imagine Auschwitz and all the
horrors.” Okay. Then, you have the Anglo-Saxon,

00:08:53.350 --> 00:09:00.270
American and so on, toilets which are mixed
its--not doesn’t matter where the hole is

00:09:00.270 --> 00:09:06.510
because it's all full of water so that the
shit floats freely there. Now, I was always

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:13.140
intrigued by this, I asked my friend’s architects
in one of the other country, "Why this?" And

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:19.260
they try to give me utilitarian answers, like,
Germans said; isn’t it natural to inspect

00:09:19.260 --> 00:09:26.029
your shit? French said, if shit smells, let's
get rid of it. Americans and English men said,

00:09:26.029 --> 00:09:30.480
let's be practical, it should float in water
so that it doesn’t smell and so on. But

00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:37.440
obviously, it's not purely a utilitarian level.
Then I asked myself a simple question, "Where

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:43.680
did they already hear, this trinity?" Let's
call it a French-German-English-Anglo-Saxon

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:54.380
civilization. Do you know that already 200
years ago, there was around Hegel’s in French

00:09:54.380 --> 00:10:01.130
evolution time. There was this popular idea
among philosophers and so on about so called

00:10:01.130 --> 00:10:07.850
European trinity, claiming that the spiritual
backbone or fundamental structure of Europe

00:10:07.850 --> 00:10:14.360
is composed of these three nations. Each of
the three stands for a certain political principle

00:10:14.360 --> 00:10:22.130
and for a certain sphere of society. Germans
are politically conservative and instead of

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:30.830
society privilege there is--the Germans said,
a nation of poets, thinkers and so on, culture.

00:10:30.830 --> 00:10:38.290
France is a revolutionary and the preferred
political sphere is politics. Anglo-Saxon

00:10:38.290 --> 00:10:43.600
universe is more, how do you call it, liberal
centrist, utilitarian, the political sphere

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:49.529
is economy. And then I got it. That’s it,
that's the key. French revolutionary, shit

00:10:49.529 --> 00:10:55.390
disappears; liquidate it as soon as possible.
You Anglo-Saxon, more pragmatic, float it

00:10:55.390 --> 00:10:59.980
there, let's see how it is, utilitarian approach.
Germans, metaphysical and poets, reflect on

00:10:59.980 --> 00:11:05.500
it and so on, you know, conserve it. And then
I spoke with architects and they admitted

00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:12.710
it, crazy as it may sound. That’s the only
way to ultimately account for a totally vulgar

00:11:12.710 --> 00:11:17.680
object like the concrete structure of a toilet.
You see now my point which is slightly more

00:11:17.680 --> 00:11:23.280
serious--not only a tasteless joke—that
even to account for the most elementary, vulgar

00:11:23.280 --> 00:11:31.640
object how it is structured--the goal, I wouldn’t
say worldview but basic attitude towards civilization

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:39.360
and so on, it’s not just a utilitarian object-—this
is what interests me, this type of ideology.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:46.060
Ideology which is, all this set of cultural
and so on prejudices which structure our daily

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:52.839
lives and you don’t even have to be fully
aware of them, especially today in our so

00:11:52.839 --> 00:11:59.540
called “cynical era” where very interesting
things are happening. How do we deal with

00:11:59.540 --> 00:12:05.170
ideology today?--Maybe you know it, it’s
also endlessly in Google—-the wonderful

00:12:05.170 --> 00:12:11.250
anecdote about Niels Bhor, you know Copenhagen,
the quantum physics guy. The story is a wonderful

00:12:11.250 --> 00:12:17.640
one. The story is that, once a friend visited
him in Demark, in the countryside where he

00:12:17.640 --> 00:12:23.490
had a house—for, go there on weekend, whatever--and
the friend, also a scientist saw above the

00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:29.170
entrance a horseshoe—-I don’t know how
it is here but in Europe, horse shoe above

00:12:29.170 --> 00:12:35.680
the entrance door is a superstitious item
destined to prevent evil spirits to enter

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:42.600
the house-—So, the shocked friend ask him,
“Wait a minute. Are you crazy? Why do you

00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:45.710
have this here, do you believe in it? Aren’t
you a scientist?” Niels Bhor answered him,

00:12:45.710 --> 00:12:48.600
“My God! I’m not crazy, I’m a scientist.
Of course I don’t believe in this thing.”

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:52.180
Then the friend asked him, “If you don’t
believe in it, why do you have it there?”

00:12:52.180 --> 00:12:58.890
Ahh, he gave a wonderful answer--Niels Bhor—he
said, “Of course I don’t believe in it

00:12:58.890 --> 00:13:04.339
but I have it there because I was told that
it works even if you don’t believe in it.”

00:13:04.339 --> 00:13:09.140
That’s how ideology functions today, we
are all cynics—-who will believes what and

00:13:09.140 --> 00:13:16.840
so on but we somehow rely on it that it will
work even if you don’t believe in it [INDISTINCT].

00:13:16.840 --> 00:13:22.970
We, in this sense, we live in a cynical era,
not cynical in the usual sense, bad people

00:13:22.970 --> 00:13:28.709
manipulating, but in a much more refined way.
We practice beliefs without believing in them

00:13:28.709 --> 00:13:36.459
as it were. And this is what fascinates me
in ideology. Especially today, the old image

00:13:36.459 --> 00:13:42.110
of ideology was, you have some explicit beliefs
and then privately you let it know, “Oh,

00:13:42.110 --> 00:13:47.110
I’m not crazy as that,” and so on. Today,
it’s the opposite, what was most private

00:13:47.110 --> 00:13:52.610
is now public and vice versa-—privately,
we like to play that we are not crazy to believe

00:13:52.610 --> 00:14:00.240
in some stupid ideology we just--what is ideology
today, explicitly? I think some kind of vaguely

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:06.640
Dalai Lama spiritualized hedonism, no? It’s
no longer, do this, sacrifice yourself—-inspite

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:11.560
of what Republicans are saying they—-just
react to it, basically ideology today is some

00:14:11.560 --> 00:14:20.560
kind of a vague injunction, be truly yourself,
realize your potentials or whatever and so

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:29.360
on and so on. But I claim we believe much
more than we appear to believe. We obey or

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:39.959
whichever way you put it much more than we
appear to do. And this again, is what all

00:14:39.959 --> 00:14:48.660
these tension between, let me call it, explicit
beliefs or absence of beliefs and this cobweb

00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:55.750
of-—to put it in the terms of your great
philosopher, Donald Rumsfeld—-of the unknown

00:14:55.750 --> 00:14:59.700
knowns, this is the crucial dimension. At
the end—-I hope I would have time, I would

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:05.920
really like to mention briefly even the whole
Sarah Palin phenomenon, I think is--you cannot

00:15:05.920 --> 00:15:15.870
understand it without, not toilets, let’s
forget that but--sorry. Okay, let me go a

00:15:15.870 --> 00:15:20.850
little bit further here, did you noticed another
extremely interesting phenomenon about which

00:15:20.850 --> 00:15:27.310
I’ve written and which points in the same
direction. What my friend, Austrian philosopher,

00:15:27.310 --> 00:15:34.149
Robert Pfaller—-you can Google him to be
tasteless, you know, I will endlessly repeat

00:15:34.149 --> 00:15:40.959
this joke being here. At least on the German
Google, you find him. He proposed a wonderful

00:15:40.959 --> 00:15:49.680
category of Interpassivity. The idea is, that
it’s not only that, we like in what we philosophers

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:55.600
call, Coming of Reason, that we like to manipulate
others. So, you see in the back others are

00:15:55.600 --> 00:16:01.680
active for you. Robert Pfaller drew attention
to a much more mysterious phenomenon, opposite

00:16:01.680 --> 00:16:10.260
one, of what he calls Interpassivity where
we transpose onto the other our passive reaction,

00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:15.930
others are passive for us. The most elementary
phenomenon and I love it, this, I think this

00:16:15.930 --> 00:16:22.880
is arguably the greatest contribution of American
civilization to world cultural heritage—-Canned

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:29.420
laughter on TV. You know, when this-—just
think about it, it’s a much more mysterious

00:16:29.420 --> 00:16:36.310
phenomenon than it may appear. It’s not,
as some wrong Pavlovian psychologist think,

00:16:36.310 --> 00:16:41.649
the function of you hearing the laughter there
as part of the soundtrack is not automatically

00:16:41.649 --> 00:16:49.110
to trigger your laughter. No, it works so
that literally the TV set laughs for you-—at

00:16:49.110 --> 00:16:55.930
least that’s how it works with me. Really
the same thing as--remember those, I always

00:16:55.930 --> 00:17:01.389
like them, in Tibetan Buddhism those praying
wheels or mills and so on where you write

00:17:01.389 --> 00:17:06.990
down the prayer, you turn it around or even
better you let the wind turn it around and

00:17:06.990 --> 00:17:11.980
then you can masturbate, whatever, it doesn’t
matter-—objectively you pray. You pray to—-here

00:17:11.980 --> 00:17:16.550
it’s the same, it laughs for you-—that’s
my experience, you know, in the evening you

00:17:16.550 --> 00:17:22.840
arrive home, dead tired, you put on some stupid
show with canned laughter on TV, Cheers, Friends,

00:17:22.840 --> 00:17:28.910
whatever and you don’t even laugh—-the
mystery is admitted at the end of the show,

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:34.830
you feel relief as if you have laughed, that’s
the mystery, how it works. In my thesis—-back

00:17:34.830 --> 00:17:43.059
to Donald Rumsfeld topic—-is that it’s
the same with beliefs, it’s not so much

00:17:43.059 --> 00:17:50.900
that we believe, we need as it where another
one to believe for us. From—-this is how

00:17:50.900 --> 00:17:55.790
our ritual functions, for example, take Santa
Clause, I mean, of course nobody believes,

00:17:55.790 --> 00:18:01.180
I mean, parents, if you ask parents they said,
“No. We are not crazy. We pretend to believe

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:05.000
not to disappoint our children,” but I can
guarantee if you ask then the children they

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.711
said, “No. I’m not crazy. We pretend to
believe not to disappoint our parents and

00:18:08.711 --> 00:18:15.700
to get presents and so on...” You got the
point, nobody has to believe only if every

00:18:15.700 --> 00:18:23.520
individual actually existing presupposes another
agency to believe then, belief functions—-the

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:29.179
whole system of believe functions. The first
to use this structure consciously, politically,

00:18:29.179 --> 00:18:34.450
you know, the old Israeli Prime Minister Golda
Meir, who when asked, “Do you believe in

00:18:34.450 --> 00:18:39.919
God?” Of course she didn’t, I mean, that’s
the irony. Israel who makes this claim of

00:18:39.919 --> 00:18:45.990
the West Bank like, “God gave us this land”
and I like it for that, about the misunderstanding,

00:18:45.990 --> 00:18:52.549
is the most atheist country in the world.
According to statistic that I read there,

00:18:52.549 --> 00:19:01.530
between 60 and 70 percent of the Israeli Jews
don’t believe in God. And the irony is that--so,

00:19:01.530 --> 00:19:05.390
Golda Meir was asks this, her answer was,
“No. I don’t believe in God,” No, she

00:19:05.390 --> 00:19:10.650
did not, she just answered, “I believe in
Jewish people and Jewish people believe in

00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:17.400
God.” But the point is that, there are no
individual Jews who have really to believe

00:19:17.400 --> 00:19:24.919
in God. Everybody just has to evoke this specter,
and so, the most terrifying experience is

00:19:24.919 --> 00:19:29.960
when you learn not that you don’t believe
but that the other which was in a way the

00:19:29.960 --> 00:19:35.830
guarantor of your belief doesn’t believe.
If you know a little bit of literature, that’s

00:19:35.830 --> 00:19:42.020
so shocking. You remember Age of Innocence,
Edith Wharton—-at the end, the guy-—okay,

00:19:42.020 --> 00:19:50.020
I speak in cinema terms—-Daniel Day Lewis
is told by his son that Winona Ryder, his

00:19:50.020 --> 00:20:00.320
dead wife, knew all the time about his affair
with Michelle Pfeiffer but pretended not to

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:07.950
know. When he learns--everything gets ruined.
That’s I think our much more fundamental

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:15.540
need than directly to believe, to have another
one as protected innocence. So let me go on

00:20:15.540 --> 00:20:22.380
